FBIS3-51815 "drlat016_b_94006" FBIS-LAT-94-016 Document Type:Daily Report 26 Jan 1994 Bermuda Haiti Chamber President Questions Sanctions' Double Standard FL2401230194 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in Creole 1230 GMT 24 Jan 94 FL2401230194 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio Language: Creole Article Type:BFN [Excerpt] Chamber of Deputies President Frantz Robert Monde does not agree that the international community should increase sanctions against the country. According to Deputy Monde, the sanctions have never done anything positive for the country's crisis, have only made the rich richer, and the poor poorer. Monde asks the international community to revise its behavior in the Haitian crisis. [Begin recording, in French] I think the international community has gotten off to a bad start with... [changes thought] Given the stand it has taken, the international community has not played the role of arbitrator. It must readjust its fire: Adopting further measures against Haiti would be a grave error, not to mention an aberration, because -- let us be honest -- the agreement was violated by the Army, it says. Let us accept that as a fait accompli. But Aristide also violated the Washington agreement even at the United Nations tribunal. No sanctions were imposed against Aristide. Why are there two sets of standards? [passage omitted] [end recording]
